    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div xml:id="KT398-kilavi">
                <p type="edition">pirivuṇarttiya tōḻiyiṟ “talaimakaṉ pirintu viṉaimuṭittu varun
                    tuṇaiyum āṟṟiyuḷarāvar” eṉṟu ulakiyaṉmēl vaittu uraittāṭkut talaimakaḷ āṟṟāmai
                    mītūrac colliyatu. </p>


                <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered in order to suppress the lack of
                    strength by HER to the one who told [her], that it be fixed in the world that
                    “there are also mates who have the strength, when HE separates, finishes [his]
                    work [and] comes [back]”, [namely] the confidante, who announced separation. </p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="KT398">
                <lg type="edition">
                    <l> tēṟṟā maṉṟē tōḻi taṇṇeṉat</l>
                    <l> tūṟṟun tuvalait tuyarkūr kālaik</l>
                    <l> kayalē ruṇkaṭ kaṉaṅkuḻai makaḷir</l>
                    <l> kaipuṇai yāka neypeytu māṭṭiya</l>
                    <l> cuṭartuya reṭuppum puṉkaṇ mālai</l>
                    <l> yarumpeṟaṟ kātalar vanteṉa viruntayarpu</l>
                    <l> meymmali yuvakaiyi ṉeḻutaru</l>
                    <l> kaṇkali ḻukupaṉi yarakku vōrē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <l> It is not, <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">aṉṟē</term> is understood as an expletive by Cām.,
                        which means he sees the mood as purely negative, while the rendering given
                        above only contains the implication that the one who will wipe away the
                        tears is not (yet?) there. T.V.G. explains that <term xml:lang="ta">aṉṟu </term>
                        can have a function similar to that of <term xml:lang="ta">maṉṟa</term> :
                        "we definitely don't know anyone ...".</note> friend, that we don't know
                        someone</l>
                    <l> who would wipe away the tears shed by crying eyes,</l>
                    <l> arising from joy welling up in the body, <note place="foot">This means tears
                        of joy; <term xml:lang="ta">uvakaiyiṉ</term> is marked as an oblique and
                        thus cannot be subject to <term xml:lang="ta">eḻu tarum.</term>
                        </note></l>
                    <l rend="indent"> when we were engaged in [preparing] a feast, for the lover
                        difficult to obtain has come,</l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> on sorrowful evening, which raises misery with the glow</l>
                    <l rend="indent3"> kindled, after oil has been poured, as a support <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">kai puṇai āka</term> : Cām. glosses here <term xml:lang="ta">karuvi</term> "tool", which presumably means (as also
                        T.V.G. renders it) "with the help of the hands". But that would be an odd
                        statement – how else is one supposed to kindle a lamp if not with the hands?
                        Moreover this would not account for <term xml:lang="ta">āka</term> . Might
                        it not rather mean a support in the sense of an occupation for the hand made
                        devoid of action by misery, that is, SHE clings to the daily tasks like the
                        kindling of the fire?</note> for the hands</l>
                    <l rend="indent4"> of women with thick ear-rings [and] carp-like collyrium eyes,</l>
                    <l rend="indent5"> at a time abounding in misery with spray spreading coolly.</l>


                </lg>
            </div>
